<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName authority="Prokop &amp; Nel, 2011" authorityName="Prokop &amp; Nel" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" genus="Lodevohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lodevohymen" order="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lodevohymen</taxonomicName>
shares with the diaphanopterodean taxa 
<taxonomicName authority="Tillyard, 1924" authorityName="Tillyard" authorityYear="1924" class="Insecta" family="Asthenohymenidae" genus="Asthenohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asthenohymen" order="Diaphanopterodea" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Asthenohymen</taxonomicName>
Tillyard, 1924 (including 
<taxonomicName authority="Riek, 1976" authorityName="Riek" authorityYear="1976" class="Insecta" family="Scytohymenidae" genus="Karoohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Karoohymen" order="Megasecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Karoohymen</taxonomicName>
Riek, 1976) (
<taxonomicName family="Asthenohymenidae" lsidName="" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" rank="family">Asthenohymenidae</taxonomicName>
Tillyard, 1924) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Zalessky, 1937" authorityName="Zalessky" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Biarmohymenidae" genus="Biarmohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Biarmohymen" order="Diaphanopterodea" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Biarmohymen</taxonomicName>
Zallesky, 1937 (
<taxonomicName family="Biarmohymenidae" lsidName="" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" rank="family">Biarmohymenidae</taxonomicName>
Zallesky, 1937), but also with the megasecopteran taxa 
<taxonomicName authority="Tillyard, 1924" authorityName="Tillyard" authorityYear="1924" class="Insecta" family="Protohymenidae" genus="Permohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Permohymen" order="Megasecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Permohymen</taxonomicName>
Tillyard, 1924, 
<taxonomicName authority="Martynov, 1932" authorityName="Martynov" authorityYear="1932" class="Insecta" family="Protohymenidae" genus="Ivahymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ivahymen" order="Megasecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ivahymen</taxonomicName>
Martynov, 1932, 
<taxonomicName authority="Tillyard, 1924" authorityName="Tillyard" authorityYear="1924" class="Insecta" family="Protohymenidae" genus="Protohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Protohymen" order="Megasecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Protohymen</taxonomicName>
Tillyard, 1924 (
<taxonomicName family="Protohymenidae" lsidName="" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" rank="family">Protohymenidae</taxonomicName>
Tillyard, 1924), 
<taxonomicName authority="Martynov, 1937" authorityName="Martynov" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Scytohymenidae" genus="Scytohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scytohymen" order="Megasecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scytohymen</taxonomicName>
Martynov, 1937, 
<taxonomicName authority="Shcherbakov, 2009" authorityName="Shcherbakov" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Scytohymenidae" genus="Oceanoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oceanoptera" order="Megasecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Oceanoptera</taxonomicName>
Shcherbakov, 2009 (in 
<bibRefCitation author="Shcherbakov, DE" journalOrPublisher="Russian Entomological Journal" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" pagination="7 - 16" title="Permian insects from the Russky Island, South Primorye." volume="18" year="2009">Shcherbakov et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName authority="Rohdendorf, 1940" authorityName="Rohdendorf" authorityYear="1940" class="Insecta" family="Scytohymenidae" genus="Tshekardohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tshekardohymen" order="Megasecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tshekardohymen</taxonomicName>
Rohdendorf, 1940 (
<taxonomicName family="Scytohymenidae" lsidName="" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" rank="family">Scytohymenidae</taxonomicName>
Martynov, 1937), the presence of basal fusion of M with CuA (
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter, FM" editor="Moore, RC" journalOrPublisher="The Geological Society of America and the University of Kansas, Boulder, Colorado" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" title="Superclass Hexapoda" volumeTitle="Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology" year="1992">Carpenter 1992</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Riek, EF" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Natal Museum" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" pagination="755 - 789" title="New Upper Permian insects from Natal, South Africa" volume="22" year="1976">Riek 1976</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shcherbakov, DE" journalOrPublisher="Russian Entomological Journal" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" pagination="7 - 16" title="Permian insects from the Russky Island, South Primorye." volume="18" year="2009">Shcherbakov et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). This important character together with a very similar pattern of venation present in all these taxa would suggest that their attribution to different orders is weakly supported.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Nevertheless 
<taxonomicName authority="Prokop &amp; Nel, 2011" authorityName="Prokop &amp; Nel" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" genus="Lodevohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lodevohymen" order="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lodevohymen</taxonomicName>
strongly differs from all these taxa in the broad areas between C and ScP and between ScP and RA without apical 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘pterostigma’">'pterostigma'</normalizedToken>
-like structure. Other 
<taxonomicName genus="Diaphanopterodea" lsidName="Diaphanopterodea" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" rank="genus">Diaphanopterodea</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Brongniart, 1885" authorityName="Brongniart" authorityYear="1885" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Megasecoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Megasecoptera" order="Malvales" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Megasecoptera</taxonomicName>
have not a long fusion CuA-M in basal part of wing (
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter, FM" editor="Moore, RC" journalOrPublisher="The Geological Society of America and the University of Kansas, Boulder, Colorado" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" title="Superclass Hexapoda" volumeTitle="Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology" year="1992">Carpenter 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Hong, 1985" authorityName="Hong" authorityYear="1985" class="Insecta" family="Bardohymenidae" genus="Sunohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sunohymen" order="Megasecoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sunohymen</taxonomicName>
Hong, 1985, currently included into the 
<taxonomicName family="Protohymenidae" lsidName="" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" rank="family">Protohymenidae</taxonomicName>
, shares with 
<taxonomicName authority="Prokop &amp; Nel, 2011" authorityName="Prokop &amp; Nel" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" genus="Lodevohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lodevohymen" order="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lodevohymen</taxonomicName>
the rather broad areas between C and ScP and RA, but they differ in RP with only two branches in the former. Also all its structures of basal half of 
<pageBreakToken pageId="7" pageNumber="48" start="start">wing</pageBreakToken>
are unknown, so that its attribution to the 
<taxonomicName family="Protohymenidae" lsidName="" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" rank="family">Protohymenidae</taxonomicName>
, family in which M is basally fused to CuA, remains undemonstrated (
<bibRefCitation author="Hong, Y-c" journalOrPublisher="Entomotaxonomia" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" pagination="83 - 91" title="New fossil genera and species of Shanxi Formation in Xishan of Taiyuan" volume="7" year="1985">Hong 1985</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName authority="Prokop &amp; Nel, 2011" authorityName="Prokop &amp; Nel" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" genus="Lodevohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lodevohymen" order="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lodevohymen</taxonomicName>
is obviously strongly different from all other 
<taxonomicName genus="Diaphanopterodea" lsidName="Diaphanopterodea" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" rank="genus">Diaphanopterodea</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Brongniart, 1885" authorityName="Brongniart" authorityYear="1885" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Megasecoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Megasecoptera" order="Malvales" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Megasecoptera</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName authority="Prokop &amp; Nel, 2011" authorityName="Prokop &amp; Nel" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" genus="Lodevohymen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lodevohymen" order="Palaeoptera incertae sedis" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lodevohymen</taxonomicName>
could be better attributed to the 
<taxonomicName genus="Diaphanopterodea" lsidName="Diaphanopterodea" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" rank="genus">Diaphanopterodea</taxonomicName>
rather than to the 
<taxonomicName authority="Brongniart, 1885" authorityName="Brongniart" authorityYear="1885" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Megasecoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Megasecoptera" order="Malvales" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Megasecoptera</taxonomicName>
for the strong convexity of the basally connected veins R, M, and CuA, forming a curve. Nevertheless, as already noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter, FM" editor="Moore, RC" journalOrPublisher="The Geological Society of America and the University of Kansas, Boulder, Colorado" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" title="Superclass Hexapoda" volumeTitle="Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology" year="1992">Carpenter (1992)</bibRefCitation>
, it is very difficult to attribute isolated wings of this kind to one of these two orders. It is better to avoid creating a new family as the phylogeny of these two orders is still to be done and the limits of the described families not clearly defined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
